<p>&#8220;Conjugated nouns,&#8221; offered by Ohio State University linguist Arnold M. Zwicky in <a href="https://archive.org/details/stx_Verbatim_The_Language_Quarterly_v1n4_1975-02/page/6/mode/2up"><em>Verbatim</em></a> in 1975:</p>
<p>I steal the keel. I stole the coal. I have stolen the colon.<br />
They choose the hues. They chose the hose. They have chosen the hosen.<br />
They mow the banks of the row. They mowed the banks of the road. They have mown the banks of the Rhone.<br />
I do it with the buoys. I did it with the biddies. I have done it with the bunnies.</p>
<p><a href="https://digitalcommons.butler.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=3366&#038;context=wordways">Mike Anglin</a> took this up in <a href="https://digitalcommons.butler.edu/wordways/vol21/iss3/"><em>Word Ways</em></a> in 1988:</p>
<p>I tear the hair; I tore the whore; I have torn the horn.<br />
I see the sea; I saw the saw; I have seen the scene.<br />
I draw the law; I drew the loo; I have drawn the lawn.<br />
I throw the bow; I threw the boo; I have thrown the bone.<br />
I sink the mink; I sank the manque; I have sunk the monk.<br />
I choose the booze; I chose the bows; I have chosen the bosun.<br />
I weave the leaves; I wove the loaves; I have woven the love-ins.<br />
I forsake the cake; I forsook the cook; I have forsaken the whole mess.</p>
<p>Philip M. Cohen added, &#8220;I scare for the mare; I score for the more; I have scorn for the morn.&#8221;</p>
